However, the DSM is not accurate. All Cluster B personality disorders have Kernberg's Borderline Personality ORGANIZATION (BPO) in common.  NPD occurs as a result of a person developing a pathological [grandiose] false self as a defense against the underlying BPO.  Relatedly, the maximum severity level of NPD abuts Antisocial Personality Disorder (Sociopathy/Psychopathy: a subset of severe NPD with zero empathy and zero desire for relationships), and can present with behavior that mimics BPD or APD/Psychopathy such that mental health practitioners Iacking psychoanalytic/psychodynamic training mistakenly diagnose comorbidity of BPD and NPD.  If a person's behavior sometimes fits BPD criteria, sometimes NPD, sometimes displaying elements of Sociopathy/Psychopathy, that is a syndrome occurring within the severe NPD population known as Malignant Narcissism.  Malignant Narcissists' behavior can be virtually indistinguishable from that of psychopaths in that they lack a conscience; however, they desire some type of connection with (a) love object(s).  Additionally, like Borderlines, they can be clingy and fear abandonment, experience extreme paranoia and/or psychosis, and many engage in self harm and/or suicidal ideation.  Malignant Narcissism can look just like BPD, but the self harm and suicidality are born of sadism and omnipotent control, not masochism and self-loathing (although self-loathing is at the core of BPO and all of the associated Cluster B personality disorders).  So if a person find themselves "walking on eggshells", but their partner ditches them - in contrast to the abandonment-fearing personality type (BPD) described in "I hate you, don't leave me" - they have found a malignant narcissist.  Expect no differently or less from them than you would from a psychopath.  It is worth distinguishing malignant narcissism from BPD, because the prognosis for treatment as I understand it is pretty close to zero.  Do not waste time thinking that DBT might help these BPD lookalikes, for they are simply O2-wasting humanoids with no redeeming qualities and no potential for self-reflection and desire for change.  BPD and NPD are mutually exclusive in theory and practice, but understanding the finer points is critical.

Abandon the DSM; Kernberg is the key (read "borderline conditions and pathological narcissism").
